\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 1. S. halepense} (L.) Pers., {\i Syn. Pl.}{\b  1}: 101 (1805). Perennial with abundant creeping rhizomes; stems 50-150 cm. Panicle 10-30 cm, lanceolate, the ultimate racemes bearing up to 5 pairs of spikelets. Sessile spikelets 4·5-5·5 mm, ellipsoid; awn 10-16 mm, or absent. Pedicellate spikelets 4·5-6 mm, narrowly lanceolate, purplish. 2n = 40, 41, 42, 43.{\i  Dry, open habitats. Possibly native in the E. Mediterranean region; widely naturalized as a weed and ruderal in S. & S.C. Europe}. [Al Az Bl Bu Co *Cr Cz Ga *Gr He Hs Hu It Ju Lu Rm Rs (W, K) Sa Si *Tu. ({\i N. Africa, S.W. Asia.})
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 2. S. sudanense} (Piper) Stapf in Oliver,{\i  Fl. Trop. Afr.}{\b  9}: 113 (1917). Annual; stems 150-300 cm. Panicle 15-30 cm, ovate to pyramidal, lax, the racemes bearing 2-5 pairs of spikelets. Sessile spikelets 6-7·5 mm, ellipsoid; awn 10-16 mm. Pedicellate spikelets 5·5-8 mm, narrowly lanceolate.{\i  Cultivated as a fodder crop in S.E. & E.C. Europe.} [Au Bu Cz Hu Rm Rs (W, K, E).] ({\i Sudan}.)
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 3. S. bicolor} (L.) Moench, {\i Meth}. 207 (1794). Like {\b 2} but very variable; sessile spikelets 4-6 mm, ovoid to subglobose, persistent.{\i  Cultivated mainly as a grain crop. S., S.E. & S.C. Europe}. [Au Bu Co Cz Ga Gr Hs Hu It Ju Lu Rm Rs (C, W, K, E).] ({\i Tropical Africa; widely cultivated elsewhere in the tropics}.)
\par

